{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-factory/research-synthesis.md'","aggregated_output":"# WakeTask Research Synthesis\n\n## Inputs and evidence quality\n- Reviewed: `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/app-store.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/reddit.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/competitors.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/research/design-patterns.md`, and `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json`.\n- Confidence: medium-high. Evidence is directionally consistent across App Store listings, Reddit pain mining, competitor mapping, and design-pattern abstraction, but App Store review scraping was partial rather than a full quantitative corpus.\n- Design evidence: the Mobbin path was session-gated, so design guidance relies on Apple HIG, competitor patterns, and SwiftAIBoilerplatePro DesignSystem references.\n\n## Target user and urgent problem\n- Target user: heavy sleepers and chronic snoozers with real morning consequences such as work, school, caregiving, shift transitions, and ADHD-like autopilot dismissal patterns.\n- Urgent problem: users do not trust default alarms or conventional challenge alarms to reliably convert \"alarm fired\" into \"fully awake and out of bed,\" and they strongly resent ad-heavy wake flows.\n\n## Jobs-to-be-done\n1. Ensure I am physically and cognitively awake before alarm dismissal is possible.\n2. Prevent relapse into sleep after first dismissal via verification and escalation.\n3. Trust that alarms will trigger reliably when consequences are real.\n4. Keep wake enforcement strict without creating punitive or chaotic mornings.\n5. Maintain privacy and dignity while using camera, object, and accountability mechanics.\n6. Move from waking up to starting the first planned morning action.\n\n## Top complaint themes and quoted evidence summaries\n- Reliability distrust and bypass anxiety.\n- Evidence summary: users repeatedly seek alarms that are \"impossible to dismiss half-asleep\" and discuss failures where alarms are missed or too easy to circumvent.\n- Ad and monetization rage during wake moments.\n- Evidence summary: Reddit threads call out Alarmy ad frustration and switching intent for cleaner wake UX.\n- Static missions become autopilot-able.\n- Evidence summary: users report they can brute-force repeated challenge types, then return to bed.\n- Friction overreach and lockout risk.\n- Evidence summary: challenge apps can feel too punishing when users are time-constrained, creating stress and churn.\n- Privacy discomfort in social and camera flows.\n- Evidence summary: users like photo/object effectiveness but want clear, local-first handling and non-invasive accountability.\n\n## Competitor strengths and weaknesses\n- Strengths:\n  - Alarmy and similar incumbents prove demand for missions, loud alarms, anti-snooze behavior, and wake checks.\n  - Sleep/wellness leaders such as Sleep Cycle and RISE are strong at long-term behavior framing and analytics.\n  - New challengers experiment quickly with single strong mechanics such as steps, scan, stakes, and social nudges.\n- Weaknesses:\n  - Reliability claims are often opaque; users lack auditable trust signals.\n  - Many apps optimize for dismissal friction but not first task execution after waking.\n  - Monetization pressure, especially ads at wake time, is a recurrent trust breaker.\n  - Tone and UX can skew either sterile utility or intrusive gimmick.\n\n## Feature opportunity matrix\n| Opportunity | Evidence | User pain | MVP feature | Differentiation | Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Reliability ledger + alarm health | Repeated reliability distrust in App Store and Reddit research | \"I cannot risk missing critical mornings\" | Per-alarm execution timeline, fail reason logs, delivery diagnostics | Turns reliability from claim into transparent proof | Medium |\n| Adaptive anti-autopilot mission engine | Users report static tasks become routine | \"I solve it half asleep and go back to bed\" | Dynamic rotation across math, scan, movement, and photo/object tasks with adaptive difficulty | Personalized anti-autopilot wake friction | Medium |\n| Post-dismiss wake contract | Demand for wake-check and escalation loops | \"I dismiss and relapse\" | Timed wake-check with escalation path if ignored | Focus on sustained wakefulness, not just dismissal | Low |\n| No-ad critical wake path | Ad frustration appears as churn driver | \"Morning ads destroy trust\" | Zero interstitial ads during active alarm and immediate post-dismissal flows | Trust-first wake UX in a category known for ad friction | Low |\n| Privacy-explicit challenge processing | Camera and social discomfort despite feature effectiveness | \"I need this to work without surveillance vibes\" | On-device mission validation messaging plus private accountability circle | Privacy as product surface, not policy footnote | Medium |\n| First-task bridge | Competitors stop at wake event | \"I wake up but lose momentum\" | Attach one required first micro-task after wake completion | Moves from alarm app to morning execution tool | High |\n\n## Differentiation thesis (App Store 4.3-safe)\nWakeTask should be positioned as a reliability and morning-execution app, not a template challenge alarm clone: it combines auditable alarm reliability, adaptive anti-autopilot wake missions, a post-dismiss wake contract, and a post-wake first-task bridge.\n\n4.3 hardening rationale:\n- Distinct value is the reliability ledger + wake contract + first-task execution system as one integrated behavior loop.\n- Feature design avoids superficial reskinning of mission alarms by introducing outcome proof and execution continuation.\n- Messaging should emphasize \"wake certainty to first action\" instead of generic \"loud alarm plus puzzles\" phrasing.\n- Design patterns should use SwiftAIBoilerplatePro components and Apple HIG principles, not copied competitor screens, assets, or language.\n\n## Design direction\n- Tone: high-trust, calm, serious; avoid gimmicky guilt, social shaming, or creepy messaging.\n- Setup: use a trust-first alarm setup wizard that explains iOS limits, permission rationale, anti-cheat boundaries, and wake-check behavior before prompts.\n- Configuration: provide a mission stack composer with reorderable tasks, difficulty chips, expected dismissal time, and clear strictness levels.\n- Active alarm: use a focused full-screen alarm state with one primary next action, high salience, large touch targets, readable countdown/status, and no monetization interruption.\n- After dismissal: present a post-dismiss wake-check card and reliability timeline so users understand what happened and what is next.\n- Privacy: explain on-device validation for camera/object tasks and avoid public leaderboards or coercive contact import.\n- DesignSystem reuse: prefer SAICard, SAIButton, SAIChip, SAIListRow, SAITag, SAIToast, SAIGlass, HapticsClient, DSColors, DSSpacing, DSTypography, and A11y helpers.\n\n## MVP scope\n- Alarm creation with per-alarm mission selection and strictness level.\n- Adaptive mission rotation with at least three mission modalities: cognitive, movement, and scan/photo/object.\n- Wake-check after dismissal with configurable escalation window.\n- Reliability ledger with human-readable log of each alarm outcome.\n- Ad-free active alarm and immediate post-dismissal experience.\n- Basic weekly wake consistency summary.\n- Segment quick-start templates for student, shift worker, chronic snoozer, and caregiver contexts.\n\n## Non-goals (MVP)\n- Full sleep-stage tracking platform.\n- Public social feed, stranger accountability mechanics, or shame-based virality.\n- Broad wellness content library such as stories, sounds, and coaching catalog.\n- Complex wearable-dependent experiences as a launch requirement.\n- Actual App Store submission or human testing tonight.\n\n## Risks and unknowns\n- iOS background and alarm constraints may limit reliability promises; claims must map to actual platform guarantees and CI evidence.\n- Adaptive strictness can feel punitive if tuning is poor; require conservative defaults and transparent overrides.\n- Camera/object missions can trigger permission drop-off; onboarding copy and privacy framing are critical.\n- First-task bridge may increase friction; validate whether users prefer strict execution or faster wake completion.\n- Mobbin research was session-gated, so visual design should remain HIG-led and avoid unverifiable pattern claims.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'cat .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec-cross-critique.md'","aggregated_output":"# Spec Cross-Critique (Gemini vs Claude vs Kimi vs DeepSeek)\n\n## Verdict\nThe candidate set is **not implementation-safe yet**. There is partial consensus on direction, but the set still contains contradictions, weak acceptance criteria, and App Store 4.3 exposure that would force an implementation agent to guess.\n\n## 1) Consensus\n- Reuse `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` as the baseline rather than starting greenfield.\n- Drive product definition from research artifacts (App Store reviews, Reddit pain points, competitor scan).\n- Implement in staged slices (foundation -> core -> interface -> integration).\n- Require automated quality checks before release handoff.\n- Include an anti-clone posture (differentiation is required, not optional).\n\n## 2) Contradictions\n- **Boilerplate reuse vs rebuild risk**:\n  - Some candidates imply heavy custom infrastructure creation (new auth/data/design layers) while others require extending existing boilerplate modules.\n  - This creates direct conflict on build scope and timeline.\n- **MVP scope boundary conflict**:\n  - Some candidates include broad “v1+” features in baseline scope; others constrain to smallest differentiated core loop.\n  - No single binding definition of what is in/out for first shippable version.\n- **Validation standard mismatch**:\n  - Some candidates treat simulator/UI smoke as sufficient; others imply full CI, test evidence, and release-ready hardening.\n  - “Done” means different things across candidates.\n- **Differentiation definition conflict**:\n  - One framing treats differentiation as UX polish; another requires unique workflow/mechanic.\n  - App Store 4.3 risk posture changes materially depending on which interpretation is used.\n\n## 3) Missing Acceptance Criteria (Critical)\nMissing or under-specified criteria that block deterministic implementation:\n- Exact **primary user journey** with start/end state and expected persisted artifacts.\n- Explicit **in-scope feature list** for first release and explicit non-goals.\n- Quantified **performance budgets** (cold launch, key interaction latency, memory ceiling).\n- Quantified **reliability budgets** (crash-free target, offline/failure behavior).\n- Quantified **quality gates** (required test suites, pass thresholds, required evidence files).\n- Explicit **data/privacy contract** (what is collected, stored, transmitted, retained, deleted).\n- Explicit **analytics event schema** and acceptance checks for event emission.\n- Explicit **error-state UX requirements** for network/API/storage failures.\n- Explicit **accessibility acceptance criteria** (Dynamic Type, VoiceOver, contrast, tap targets).\n- Explicit **App Store submission evidence checklist** tied to spec requirements.\n\n## 4) App Store 4.3 Risks\nHigh-risk language/patterns that should be rejected or rewritten:\n- “Build a [category] app like top competitors” without a defensible differentiator definition.\n- Feature sets that mirror common boilerplate templates with only cosmetic changes.\n- No required uniqueness test (e.g., differentiator must be visible in first session).\n- No anti-clone acceptance gate in final review.\n\nRequired hardening additions:\n- Define a **Differentiation Contract** with 3-5 concrete product behaviors unavailable in commodity clones.\n- Add a **4.3 Gate**: fail release if differentiators are absent from onboarding, core flow, and screenshots/metadata narrative.\n\n## 5) Boilerplate Rebuild Risks\nAny candidate requiring these without explicit “why existing module cannot be extended” is overbuilding:\n- Rebuilding DI/composition root.\n- Rebuilding design system primitives.\n- Rebuilding networking/storage abstractions already present in boilerplate.\n- Replacing module boundaries instead of adding app-specific features within them.\n\nRequired constraint:\n- Every new infrastructure component must include: `existing module evaluated`, `gap found`, `extension not viable`, `replacement cost/benefit`.\n\n## 6) Testability Gaps\nCurrent candidate set under-specifies testability in these areas:\n- No requirement-to-test traceability table.\n- No per-feature acceptance tests with deterministic setup and assertions.\n- No explicit fixtures/mocks contract for external dependencies.\n- No negative-path test requirements (timeouts, empty states, partial failures).\n- No release-blocking definition for flaky or skipped tests.\n\nMinimum fix:\n- Add a trace matrix: `Requirement ID -> implementation artifact -> test case(s) -> evidence file`.\n\n## 7) Vague / Non-Verifiable Claims (Reject As Written)\nReject terms unless converted to measurable checks:\n- “intuitive UX”\n- “fast and responsive”\n- “production-ready”\n- “secure by default”\n- “high-quality architecture”\n- “App Store ready”\n\nEach must be rewritten as:\n- measurable threshold,\n- test method,\n- evidence artifact path.\n\n## 8) Strict Merge Rules For Next Spec Revision\nThe merged spec should be rejected unless all are true:\n1. Every functional requirement has at least one acceptance test.\n2. Every non-functional requirement has a numeric threshold and verification method.\n3. Scope for first release is explicitly bounded with non-goals.\n4. Differentiation Contract exists and is validated by a 4.3 gate.\n5. No net-new infrastructure is introduced without explicit boilerplate-gap justification.\n6. “Definition of Done” is singular and evidence-based across all phases.\n\n## 9) Implementation-Ready Delta (What to add now)\n- Add requirement IDs (`FR-*`, `NFR-*`) and a full acceptance criteria table.\n- Add an anti-clone Differentiation Contract section with pass/fail checks.\n- Add an infrastructure policy section: “extend before replace” with mandatory justification template.\n- Add a verification section listing exact commands/artifacts required for phase and release gates.\n- Add a traceability matrix linking requirements, tasks, tests, and evidence outputs.\n\nIf these deltas are not applied, implementation will involve guesswork and inconsistent review outcomes.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
